</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2f2f4f><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub35.ezboard.com/ujondinsottovoce.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Jondin Sottovoce</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(1/29/02 9:23:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm15.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=577.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.supernet.net/~langston/bow.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Bard songs.</span><hr size=1> Quick response off the top of my head unfortunately I can’t go into detail right now but this is what I see. <br>
<br>
Not taking into account PvP:<br>
<br>
<br>
Denon's Bereavement is a level 59 song you don’t have to worry about that with a level 56 Bard.<br>
<br>
Song of Twilight (52) is not resisted very often, even less if you have a wind instrument in hand.  Without a wind instrument its approx –15MR, with a win instrument your looking at –29MR and with Epic your looking at –26MR.  You hit them with Occlusion of sound and even the most uber-equipped warrior has a good chance of being mezzed 2 out of 5 times.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  I assume that even if the songs last an ok duration it would be all that a bard could do to keep the player snared so singing songs to dot them down on top of that would be out of the question<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Nope we have a new Selo’s song that lasts 2 minutes, no need for snare if we don’t want to.  If it lands successfully a few times I’ll stick with it, if not I don’t concern myself with it unless I’m meleeing, in which case Amp + Epic will make sure it lands for an instant: (-132agi, -48AC, slow/snare)<br>
<br>
Keeping Occlusion on you is not an issues, once it is on you and the first successful debuff lands, it will almos always (depending on what song the bard is singing) debuff the needed stats, so landing the song again is almost always successful.  Amplification (as I stated in my other thread lasts much longer than normal songs, so twisting it with other is not neccissary every time, you can skip 3 full twist of amplification as long as you pick it back up on the 4th twist.  This leaves us at nothing but 2 songs while given your above example.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>  going toe to toe with the rogue would be one hell of a mistake<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Actually no it wouldn’t.  We (in most circumstances) have more ac than a rogue, maybe not as many hps, but that doesn’t matter if you consider our DS which (with the help of Amp and epic) is possible of just 27 with ONE song. Not to mention bards can stack DS’s (yeah it’s a bug but it works, use it you know you would).  In my test a Toe to Toe (no BS) I won with an epic equipped rogue no songs, nothing but melee loosing a little more than 2 bubbles of health.  With DS up I lost almost one bubble of health.<br>
<br>
Trust me when I say don’t stand toe to toe, our 18 DS song is also a +118 vsPoison (without Amplification but with epic equipped).  Add in amplification and you get a 27 DS a ~ 140 vsPoison<br>
<br>
When I duel a rogue I make sure I have the max DS I can provide, rather it be through my SS bracer and songs alone, or with SS bracer, songs, mage DS, Druid DS, Amplification, your looking at a ~87 DS right there alone. I can keep that on myself and chain cast my SS bp and not have to worry about much of anything but looking pretty to those watching.  That’s melee alone, lets not even talk about occlusion w/Selo’s drum of the march, and the 3 dots.  Or amp + epic + bellows for a chain casting dmg of 78 pts per pulse.  If you have a good strategy stand toe to toe with a rogue, if not stay back and bellow/dot to death its all a matter of how fast you want the fight to be, or what songs you prefer.  If you’d like more feedback I’d be happy to do so later when work settles down.<br>
